    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#buzaian-lloyd1996"/>, p. <citedRange>138</citedRange> (ph.)</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>46.2190</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>083900</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>πλί</abbr><ex cert="low">νθος</ex></expan>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Parpaing.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Squared block.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Plinto.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Buzaian and Lloyd wrote that there were three such blocks bearing the same inscription and give the length of only one with one photograph.</p>
                <p>They 'provisionally' but convincingly interpret them as blocks fallen from a wall serving for the fortification of the city of Euesperides on its 
                North-West side.</p>
                <p>As no personal name beginning with <foreign xml:lang="grc">Πλι</foreign>- is attested, the editors' idea of a mason's mark seems very convincing.</p>
            </div></body>
